# I'm afraid, don't you understand?
I'm losing, losing my very mind

481
00:43:25,047 --> 00:43:26,791
# I got to have you with me

482
00:43:26,924 --> 00:43:29,676
# I'm in such complete anguish without you

483
00:43:32,763 --> 00:43:36,808
# Baby, I'm standing
at the great abyss of love

484
00:43:36,934 --> 00:43:40,018
# And I'm teetering
Oh, darlin'

485
00:43:40,146 --> 00:43:42,719
# I promise I'll even be nice to your mama

486
00:43:42,857 --> 00:43:45,348
# Baby, please

487
00:43:45,484 --> 00:43:50,395
# Spend this night with me

488
00:43:52,825 --> 00:43:55,197
# Ooh, ah #

489
00:44:14,138 --> 00:44:16,011
Those bikes!

490
00:44:16,849 --> 00:44:18,925
(Whinnying and neighing)

491
00:44:19,059 --> 00:44:21,846
(Horse hooves clatter away)

492
00:44:29,361 --> 00:44:32,279
That is no excuse!
Search the road again!

493
00:44:42,958 --> 00:44:45,116
They're in the Eastern sector.

494
00:44:45,252 --> 00:44:47,577
I want the whole area sealed off!

495
00:45:05,105 --> 00:45:07,560
There's a used book store
somewhere around here.

496
00:45:07,691 --> 00:45:09,351
The owner is a member of the Resistance.

497
00:45:09,484 --> 00:45:14,063
- If we can find him...
- Resistance? Wait a minute.

498
00:45:14,197 --> 00:45:18,693
Don't you think it's about time
you told what this is all about?

499
00:45:18,827 --> 00:45:21,947
I'm sorry, I guess I do owe
you an explanation.

500
00:45:22,080 --> 00:45:27,121
Only a year ago I was teaching
a course in black history

501
00:45:27,252 --> 00:45:30,087
at the University of Blaupunkt.

502
00:45:30,213 --> 00:45:35,634
One night, I came home to find my father
had been arrested by the Secret Police.

503
00:45:35,760 --> 00:45:39,046
I've been trying to find him ever since.

504
00:45:39,764 --> 00:45:42,801
Wait a minute. That's Dr Flammond.

505
00:45:42,934 --> 00:45:45,639
I saw him yesterday in Flurgendorf Prison.

506
00:45:45,770 --> 00:45:48,059
Flurgendorf Prison? Is he all right?

507
00:45:48,189 --> 00:45:50,680
- He looks fine.
- Thank God, he's safe.

508
00:45:50,817 --> 00:45:53,937
We must get this information
to the Resistance.

509
00:45:54,070 --> 00:45:57,569
- Maybe they can help us.
- Let's go.

510
00:46:14,215 --> 00:46:17,631
(Trickling)

511
00:46:37,280 --> 00:46:42,155
There it is.
It's a Swedish book store.

512
00:46:45,705 --> 00:46:48,409
(Bell rings)

513
00:46:56,173 --> 00:46:58,581
(Clears throat)

514
00:47:01,929 --> 00:47:03,553
May I help you?

515
00:47:04,598 --> 00:47:06,840
My father is Dr. Paul Flammond

516
00:47:06,976 --> 00:47:10,890
I'm sorry.
I don't know a Dr. Flammond.

517
00:47:11,605 --> 00:47:15,934
He told me you may have a book
of Swedish poems by Von Brieson.

518
00:47:18,153 --> 00:47:20,775
So you are Hillary Flammond!

519
00:47:24,451 --> 00:47:28,366
What can I do for you?

520
00:47:29,373 --> 00:47:31,412
We must speak with "The Torch".

521
00:47:31,542 --> 00:47:33,700
That will be very difficult.

522
00:47:41,843 --> 00:47:44,595
But I will try to arrange it.

523
00:47:45,556 --> 00:47:47,881
Can we leave tonight?

524
00:47:51,895 --> 00:47:54,682
It is too dangerous to travel at night.

525
00:47:57,609 --> 00:48:00,480
You will be taken in the morning
to a potato farm.

526
00:48:00,612 --> 00:48:03,020
Where can we stay tonight?

527
00:48:03,156 --> 00:48:04,864
There is a loft upstairs.

528
00:48:04,991 --> 00:48:07,529
You can use that fire pole.

529
00:48:20,632 --> 00:48:27,251
(Hillary) That's OK. Don't feel bad.
It happens to lots of men the first time.

530
00:48:27,389 --> 00:48:29,465
Just relax. I'll pour you a drink.

531
00:48:29,599 --> 00:48:32,636
We can always try again
in a couple of hours,

532
00:48:32,769 --> 00:48:37,146
she said, as she laid down beside him
and caressed his chest.

533
00:48:37,273 --> 00:48:39,847
Can you believe they print this trash?

534
00:48:39,984 --> 00:48:41,858
Don't worry about it.

535
00:48:41,986 --> 00:48:46,316
You were going to tell
me something about your childhood.

536
00:48:46,449 --> 00:48:48,525
When I was a young girl,

537
00:48:48,660 --> 00:48:51,151
my uncle took me on a tropical cruise.

538
00:48:51,287 --> 00:48:53,327
But there was a terrible storm

539
00:48:53,456 --> 00:48:55,781
and the boat sank.

540
00:48:55,917 --> 00:48:58,408
I managed to swim to a deserted island

541
00:48:58,545 --> 00:49:00,870
with a young boy, named Nigel.

542
00:49:01,005 --> 00:49:03,579
Together we had to learn to survive.

543
00:49:06,552 --> 00:49:09,090
'Fortunately the ocean provided its bounty,

544
00:49:09,222 --> 00:49:12,092
'which Nigel would catch every day.

545
00:49:12,225 --> 00:49:15,309
'Later, I would forage inland
for fruit and vegetables

546
00:49:15,436 --> 00:49:20,098
'from the endless varieties
of trees and bushes all over the island.

547
00:49:20,233 --> 00:49:24,017
'We busied ourselves chopping palm
fronds and lacing them to bamboo

548
00:49:24,153 --> 00:49:26,609
'with dried seaweed and snot.

549
00:49:26,739 --> 00:49:29,942
'This not only provided us
with a safe haven from the rain.

550
00:49:30,076 --> 00:49:32,946
'But sheltered us
from the relentless Santa Ana winds

551
00:49:33,079 --> 00:49:35,866
'which would periodically
ravage the island.

552
00:49:35,998 --> 00:49:38,750
'The years passed and as we grew up,

553
00:49:38,876 --> 00:49:43,419
'we began to notice
strange new feelings awakening in us.

554
00:49:43,547 --> 00:49:46,038
'There was no one around to explain this.

555
00:49:46,175 --> 00:49:48,962
'We had to learn by ourselves.

556
00:50:18,499 --> 00:50:21,204
'Then one day he went fishing.

557
00:50:21,335 --> 00:50:24,834
'That was the last I ever saw of Nigel.

558
00:50:24,963 --> 00:50:27,964
'I spent months by myself on that island,'

559
00:50:28,092 --> 00:50:31,591
until I was finally rescued
by a passing ship.

560
00:50:31,720 --> 00:50:34,342
I'll never forget my feeling of relief.

561
00:50:34,473 --> 00:50:36,549
You can't imagine what it's like

562
00:50:36,683 --> 00:50:38,759
to be separated from your family

563
00:50:38,894 --> 00:50:40,970
at such a young age.

564
00:50:41,104 --> 00:50:42,896
I think I can.

565
00:50:46,527 --> 00:50:51,188
When I was about six years old,
my momma took me to the city.

566
00:50:51,323 --> 00:50:55,901
We went to one of those big old
department stores, and I got lost.

567
00:50:56,036 --> 00:50:58,990
They tried to page her,

568
00:50:59,122 --> 00:51:01,744
but the PA system was on the fritz.

569
00:51:02,834 --> 00:51:05,835
I never saw my momma again.

570
00:51:05,962 --> 00:51:08,714
Some people
from the cosmetics department

571
00:51:08,840 --> 00:51:11,129
fed me a bowl of soup and some bread.

572
00:51:11,259 --> 00:51:13,335
Days stretched into weeks.

573
00:51:13,470 --> 00:51:15,628
One February they got jammed up

574
00:51:15,764 --> 00:51:18,433
during the semi-annual
Lincoln's birthday sale.

575
00:51:18,558 --> 00:51:22,342
They asked me to help out
in Pre-Teen Maternity.

576
00:51:22,479 --> 00:51:25,978
Then one day I overheard
a conversation in personnel

577
00:51:26,107 --> 00:51:29,192
about them needing a new jingle
for their radio ad.

578
00:51:29,319 --> 00:51:32,937
So I picked up my guitar
and I wrote down a tune

579
00:51:33,073 --> 00:51:37,236
that had been mulling and creeping
and crawling around in my head.

580
00:51:37,369 --> 00:51:39,907
It went something like this.

581
00:51:50,090 --> 00:51:54,087
# Are you lonesome tonight?

582
00:51:54,219 --> 00:51:58,382
# Is your kitchen a sight?

583
00:51:58,515 --> 00:52:04,932
# Is your wardrobe all run down and bare?

584
00:52:06,856 --> 00:52:10,901
# Is your lipstick all smeared?

585
00:52:11,027 --> 00:52:15,072
# Are your stockings not sheer?

586
00:52:15,198 --> 00:52:21,865
# Do they make your legs
show all your hair?

587
00:52:23,331 --> 00:52:27,708
# Do the tears on your pillow

588
00:52:27,835 --> 00:52:31,418
# Roll down as you turn?

589
00:52:31,547 --> 00:52:35,711
# Do they short out the blanket?

590
00:52:35,843 --> 00:52:39,461
# And make the sheets burn?

591
00:52:39,597 --> 00:52:43,547
# Is your heart filled with pain?

592
00:52:43,684 --> 00:52:47,100
# Will you come back again?

593
00:52:47,229 --> 00:52:52,935
# Shop at Macy's and love me tonight #

594
00:52:54,028 --> 00:52:55,736
Oh, Nick.

595
00:52:56,864 --> 00:52:59,402
(Wood crunches)

596
00:53:15,966 --> 00:53:18,173
(Voice singing in German)

597
00:53:35,027 --> 00:53:38,277
Whoa! Whoa!

598
00:53:38,405 --> 00:53:40,445
Whoa!

599
00:53:40,574 --> 00:53:42,863
All right, this is it.

600
00:53:42,993 --> 00:53:45,199
I must leave you here.

601
00:53:46,497 --> 00:53:48,822
Go now, quickly.

602
00:53:48,957 --> 00:53:51,495
(Raspy coughing)

603
00:53:51,627 --> 00:53:54,877
- Is he all right?
- He caught a cold the other day.

604
00:53:55,005 --> 00:53:57,128
He's just a little hoarse.

605
00:53:57,257 --> 00:53:59,333
Giddy-up, Mario.

606
00:53:59,468 --> 00:54:04,972
# It's been a hard day's night
And I've been working like a dog... #

607
00:54:11,521 --> 00:54:14,273
- Yes?
- Is this the potato farm?

608
00:54:14,399 --> 00:54:18,728
Yes, I am Albert Potato. Who are you?

609
00:54:18,862 --> 00:54:21,982
We were sent by Sven Jorgensen.

610
00:54:26,077 --> 00:54:27,821
Come this way.

611
00:54:54,230 --> 00:54:58,442
- (French accent) What do you want?
- We wanna see "The Torch".

612
00:54:58,568 --> 00:55:01,485
No one is allowed to see "The Torch".

613
00:55:01,613 --> 00:55:07,283
But we have important information about
my father, Dr Paul Flammond.

614
00:55:07,410 --> 00:55:10,115
We shall see.

615
00:55:23,176 --> 00:55:26,046
- Nigel!
- Hillary!

616
00:55:32,810 --> 00:55:36,594
It is you. My darling, Hillary.

617
00:55:36,731 --> 00:55:39,566
If only you knew how I've yearned
for this day to come.

618
00:55:39,692 --> 00:55:44,437
Sleepless nights, lonely hours,
hoping, praying that once more

619
00:55:44,572 --> 00:55:47,857
I would gaze
into your ravishing brown eyes.

620
00:55:47,992 --> 00:55:51,740
Who is this I should thank
for bringing you back to me?

621
00:55:51,871 --> 00:55:54,872
This is Nick.
Nick Rivers, he's a friend.

622
00:55:54,999 --> 00:55:59,162
Forgive us, Mr Rivers,
if we have been less than hospitable.

623
00:55:59,295 --> 00:56:05,084
Recently we've had reason to believe
there is a traitor in the Resistance.

624
00:56:05,217 --> 00:56:08,966
Du Quois,
introduce the American to the men.

625
00:56:09,096 --> 00:56:10,840
Very well.

626
00:56:11,640 --> 00:56:17,892
This is Chevalier, Montage, Détente,

627
00:56:18,022 --> 00:56:22,518
Avant Garde, and Déjà Vu.

628
00:56:23,444 --> 00:56:26,065
Have we not met before, Monsieur?

629
00:56:26,989 --> 00:56:28,863
I don't think so.

630
00:56:33,579 --> 00:56:35,121
Over there...

631
00:56:35,247 --> 00:56:40,205
Croissant, Soufflé, Escargot,

632
00:56:40,335 --> 00:56:42,791
and Chocolate Mousse.

633
00:56:42,921 --> 00:56:45,543
(Chocolate Mousse grunts)

634
00:56:48,802 --> 00:56:52,254
Now, Mr Rivers,
what is the news that you bring us?

635
00:56:52,389 --> 00:56:55,556
I've seen Dr Flammond
in Flurgendorf prison.

636
00:56:55,684 --> 00:56:59,385
He told me the Polaris mine
will be ready on Sunday.

637
00:57:00,564 --> 00:57:01,762
<i>Sacrebleu.</i>

638
00:57:03,150 --> 00:57:05,356
We'll have to move out tonight.

639
00:57:05,485 --> 00:57:07,561
I'll be back in a moment, my darling.

640
00:57:07,696 --> 00:57:09,938
Prepare the gear for the jump.

641
00:57:10,073 --> 00:57:11,865
<i>Cordon bleu. Zut!</i>

642
00:57:11,992 --> 00:57:14,946
- I want to explain.
- What's to explain?

643
00:57:15,078 --> 00:57:18,494
I'm not the first guy who fell in love
with a girl he met in a restaurant,

644
00:57:18,623 --> 00:57:21,743
who turned out to be the daughter
of a kidnapped scientist,

645
00:57:21,877 --> 00:57:25,246
to lose her to her childhood lover
she'd last seen on a deserted island

646
00:57:25,380 --> 00:57:28,831
who, 15 years later, is the leader
of the French underground.

647
00:57:28,967 --> 00:57:32,253
It all sounds like some bad movie.

648
00:57:39,144 --> 00:57:44,482
Forget it. It'll be better for everyone
if we just forget what's happened.

649
00:57:44,608 --> 00:57:48,854
We've arranged for your safe
transportation across the border tonight.

650
00:57:48,987 --> 00:57:52,272
It's the least we can do
to show our gratitude.

651
00:57:52,407 --> 00:57:57,911
Come, my darling, let me show you
what I've done to the fallout shelter.

652
00:58:20,393 --> 00:58:22,765
Do not take it so hard, Nick.

653
00:58:22,895 --> 00:58:26,229
Life is filled with its little miseries.

654
00:58:26,357 --> 00:58:30,402
Each of us, in his own way,
must learn to deal with adversity

655
00:58:30,528 --> 00:58:33,399
in a mature and adult fashion.

656
00:58:44,500 --> 00:58:47,834
- Mind if I have a swig of this?
- Go right ahead.

657
00:58:47,962 --> 00:58:51,497
- What the hell is this stuff?
- Gasoline.

658
00:58:56,095 --> 00:59:00,140
Don't worry, my darling.
I'm sure your friend will get over it.

659
00:59:00,266 --> 00:59:02,757
He seems a good chap, really.

660
00:59:02,893 --> 00:59:05,384
How wonderful you've returned to me,

661
00:59:05,521 --> 00:59:09,056
when I desperately need you
by my side, to fight for the cause...

662
00:59:09,191 --> 00:59:12,892
- Our cause.
- Oh, Nigel, I am proud of you.

663
00:59:13,028 --> 00:59:17,607
But I'm so confused.
All these years I thought you were dead.

664
00:59:17,741 --> 00:59:20,197
And by all rights I should be.

665
00:59:20,327 --> 00:59:22,901
I floated at sea for days,
nearly unconscious.

666
00:59:23,038 --> 00:59:26,242
Then as luck would have it,
I was picked up by a passing freighter.

667
00:59:26,375 --> 00:59:29,162
I tried to get them to save you too.

668
00:59:29,295 --> 00:59:32,082
It was a foreign ship
and they didn't understand English.

669
00:59:32,256 --> 00:59:37,381
I yelled and screamed, but it only
seemed to excite them all the more.

670
00:59:37,511 --> 00:59:40,678
They took advantage of me
in ways I cannot describe.

671
00:59:40,806 --> 00:59:46,595
Oh, Nigel, it must have been awful.

672
00:59:52,484 --> 00:59:54,393
Latrine!

673
00:59:57,948 --> 01:00:01,364
- What did you find out, Latrine?
- Where are the others?

674
01:00:01,493 --> 01:00:03,367
We never had a chance.

675
01:00:03,495 --> 01:00:05,369
It was a slaughter.

676
01:00:05,497 --> 01:00:08,581
We must put a stop
to these afternoon football games.

677
01:00:08,709 --> 01:00:12,042
- Which direction did they come from?
- Up the road.

678
01:00:12,170 --> 01:00:13,546
(Gunshots)

679
01:00:13,672 --> 01:00:17,207
- Take cover!
- They're gonna kill us all.

680
01:00:25,183 --> 01:00:28,517
(Clicking of tap-heeled dancers)

681
01:00:30,939 --> 01:00:32,481
Take this.

682
01:01:38,339 --> 01:01:39,584
Grenade.

683
01:01:51,561 --> 01:01:55,095
We're running out of time.
The plane will not wait for us.

684
01:01:55,231 --> 01:01:57,307
We'll have to make a break for it.

685
01:01:57,441 --> 01:01:59,979
Rendezvous at the cafe
near the landing field.

686
01:02:00,111 --> 01:02:01,225
Wait!

687
01:02:18,754 --> 01:02:20,213
Nice shooting.

688
01:02:20,339 --> 01:02:21,502
My man!

689
01:02:46,740 --> 01:02:49,694
Good. Now everybody's accounted for.

690
01:02:49,827 --> 01:02:53,077
Here's the plan.
We'll be taking off at 1:00 am.

691
01:02:53,205 --> 01:02:55,114
What about the American?

692
01:02:55,249 --> 01:02:58,036
A truck will be here
at exactly midnight.

693
01:02:58,168 --> 01:03:01,086
He'll jump on the back
and be driven on to the border.

694
01:03:01,213 --> 01:03:05,127
Wait. Nick is the only one
who knows the inside of that prison.

695
01:03:08,595 --> 01:03:12,925
Well, Monsieur Rivers,
it seems that you have become,

696
01:03:13,058 --> 01:03:15,845
how do you say, indispensable?

697
01:03:15,978 --> 01:03:17,804
Indispensable.

698
01:03:19,231 --> 01:03:21,307
That's what I thought.

699
01:03:21,441 --> 01:03:25,391
Sorry, fellas. I've done my time
in Flurgendorf prison.

700
01:03:25,529 --> 01:03:27,984
I got a truck to meet.

701
01:03:30,909 --> 01:03:34,823
Nick, ask any price you want,
but you must help us.

702
01:03:34,955 --> 01:03:39,118
Seems as long as I know my way
around that prison, I'll never be lonely.

703
01:03:39,251 --> 01:03:41,327
I know how you feel about me.

704
01:03:41,461 --> 01:03:44,581
But put your feelings aside
for something more important.

705
01:03:44,714 --> 01:03:48,214
Like what a great cause
you and Nigel are fighting for?

706
01:03:48,343 --> 01:03:51,463
- But this was your cause too.
- My only cause is my music.

707
01:03:51,596 --> 01:03:53,719
That's exactly what I mean.

708
01:03:53,848 --> 01:03:58,925
Didn't you see the eyes of those kids
at your concert? You must help us.

709
01:03:59,062 --> 01:04:01,434
If not for me, for the cause of freedom.

710
01:04:03,817 --> 01:04:05,525
Latrine.

711
01:04:06,736 --> 01:04:10,686
- A traitor in our midst.
- Well done, Latrine.

712
01:04:10,824 --> 01:04:13,825
I see you have dealt with him
appropriately.

713
01:04:13,952 --> 01:04:15,825
Not the bird, you fool!

714
01:04:15,954 --> 01:04:19,951
This is a carrier pigeon on its way
to German headquarters.

715
01:04:20,083 --> 01:04:22,621
Look, a message.

716
01:04:22,752 --> 01:04:28,422
Resistance planning to free Flammond,
Sunday, 8:00 am.

717
01:04:28,550 --> 01:04:33,176
That means the traitor
is someone at this very table.

718
01:04:39,352 --> 01:04:44,263
Excuse me, aren't you Nick Rivers,
the American rock and roll star?

719
01:04:46,025 --> 01:04:47,899
No, I'm not.

720
01:04:48,027 --> 01:04:51,194
But you must be.
Won't you sing us one song?

721
01:04:51,322 --> 01:04:54,193
I'm sorry. You must have me confused
with somebody else.

722
01:04:54,325 --> 01:04:57,776
I'm Mel Tormé.

723
01:04:59,038 --> 01:05:00,912
Oh.

724
01:05:02,750 --> 01:05:04,458
That was close.

725
01:05:04,585 --> 01:05:08,453
- Perhaps a bit too close.
- What do you mean?

